The Multible R-Squared represents how good can be explained the log10meansalary (response) by the yearID (predictor).The bigger the Multiple R^2 is, the better. Here, the Multiple R-squared is 0.4878 which means that the correlation between response and predictor variable is low. Around 50% in variance in log10 mean salary is explained by variations in years.More specific, yearID explains 48.78% of the variation in log10meansalary.So it is definitely explanatory, but there are clearly a lot of other uncontrolled factors that also influencing log10 mean salary.

  1. Linearity: looking at the scatterplot of residuals versus yearID it seems that it do not have a linear regression because as the yearID increases the residuals are increasing but then started to decrease again. It looks like a parabola.

  2. looking three plots of residuals:

    1. Homoscedasticity: looking at the scatter of residuals versus yearID, the spread of the residuals doesnt show any indication of trend.

    2. Normality: looking at the qq plot of residuals, the points on the plot roughly form a straight diagonal line, so the normality assumption is met. Also,looking at the histogram of residuals, it looks more like a Gaussian distribution.

    3. Independence: In the scatterplot residuals arent steadily grow larger as time goes on so there is Independence.

Domain-based reason -> Only the players who have had hit the ball can score a run

Data-based reason -> The count of the second set is a number that cant be fraction (hits) whereas the first one is a number that can be a fraction.

So the Statistical analysis is that to find a balance between these two we use Poisson which for only players who have a hit.

  1. [2 + 4 points] Find the p-value for each of the predictor variables in this model using a Likelihood Ratio Test. What hypothesis does each p-value test, and what mathematically does a p-value tell you about a variable? Use this definition to say what is meant by the p-value associated to POS and to the p-value associated to height.
A <- Anova(glm1)
A

The H hypothesis is if the Hits has an effect on the Score of Runs. Since the p-value (< 2.2e-16) is smaller than 0.05, this means that the predictor is statistically significant and with large coefficient which means that if we change it it will make a big difference in Run. There is a 0.00000000000000022, chance of observing this at random.

The yearf hypothesis is if the years has an effect on the Score of Runs. Since the p-value (0.01625) is smaller than 0.05, this means that the predictor is significant and with large coefficient which means that if we change it it will make a big difference in R. There is a 0.01625 chance of observing this at random.

The POS hypothesis is if the Position of the players has an effect on the Score of Runs. Since the p-value (< 2e-16) is smaller than 0.05, this means that the predictor is important, significant and with large coefficient which means that if we change it it will make a big difference in R. There is a 0.00000000000000022, chance of observing this at random.

The height hypothesis is if the height of players has an effect on the Score of Runs. Since the p-value (0.10994) is greater than 0.05, this means that the predictor is not important and with small coefficient which means that if we change it it will not make a big difference at all in R. There is a 0.10994 chance of observing this at random.

The age hypothesis is if the age of players has an effect on the Score of Runs. Since the p-value (9.705e-05) is smaller than 0.05, this means that the predictor is important, significant and with large coefficient which means that if we change it it will make a big difference in R. There is a 9.705e-05 chance of observing this at random.

Assumptions of poisson model:

  1. Dispersion(Variance = Mean) : The red line is not flat, and it is above 0.8, so Var(x) > E(x). This is an overdispersion in the data. If the red line were under the green one, it would be underdispersed.

    1. Linearity: We can evaluate this looking at the (deviance) residuals vs fitted and seeing if the plot looks fairly flat. Comparing the red line to the black dotted one we can notice that the red line looks like a parabola so there is no linearity.

    2. Distribution: Investigating the qqplot we can see that it follows a Poisson distribution

    3. Independence: We investigate residuals as a function of order of datapoints and look for evidence of snaking. In this dataset we dont have a natural order so again cant investigate.

  1. [4 + 2 points] Fit the model on the training data, then predict on the testing data. Plot comparative ROC curves and summarise your findings.
train.model <- glm(DivWin ~ W + L + attendance, data = train.data, family = "binomial")


predtrain <- predict(train.model, type = "response")
predtest <- predict(train.model, newdata = test.data, type = "response")



roc.train <- roc(response = train.data$DivWin, predictor = predtrain, plot = TRUE, auc = TRUE, main = "ROC curve for prediction of DivWin")

roc.test<- roc(response = test.data$DivWin, predictor = predtest, plot = TRUE, auc = TRUE, add = TRUE, col = 2)

roc.train$auc
roc.test$auc
Area under the curve: 0.9517
Area under the curve: 0.9442

The ROC curves of both training and testing have a very similar shape which means that this is a good sign that the data is not overfitted to the training data.
